<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-249-684  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 249 684.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  April 1990 v3 n4 p56(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DBMS/Copy ends clumsy database file conversions. (ConceptualSoftware DBMS/Copy database conversion utility) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Falkner, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Conceptual Software's DBMS/Copy is a convenient utility thatconverts data base files among any of 65 popular file formats.andP;  Itsupports six major spreadsheets, 17 databases, and more than 40mainframe and statistical packages.andP;  The program is easy to useand has a convenient windowing interface.andP;  DBMS/Copy automaticallychanges incompatible variable names to valid ones, converts filedtypes ,and creates an error log as the user translates files.andP;  Itis especially useful in converting text or spreadsheet data intodatabase format.andP;  The $195 package may not be necessary for allusers because many programs have built-in dBASE III, Lotus 1-2-3,and comma-delimited ASCII translation functions.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Conceptual Software Inc. (products).andO;Product:   DBMS/Copy (Utility program).andO;Topic:     Utility ProgramsFile ManagementConversionEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DBMS/Copy Ends Clumsy Database File Conversions Attention, database users:you no longer have to struggle with file conversion.andP;  A handy utility fromConceptual Software, DBMS/Copy, painlessly converts information from oneformat to another.andM;The utility converts files among 65 software file formats.andP;  Most people willuse only the 6 spreadsheets and 17 databases DMBS/Copy handles, not the morethan 40 statistical and mainframe packages in its repertoire.andP;  All the bignames are there, though, and it's nice to have the smaller ones too.andP;  An $89Lite version supports 26 file formats.andM;If you understand some database basics and a little DOS, you can useDBMS/Copy.andP;  Power users can execute it from the DOS prompt by supplyingfilenames and options on the command line.andP;  Windows help novices selectformats and files.andM;You'll want DBMS/Copy if your current translation procedure is clumsy ortime-consuming.andP;  The speedy package works overtime to facilitate conversions:as you translate files, it creates an error log, changes incompatiblevariable names to valid ones, and converts field types for the best fit inthe new file.andP;  The documentation describes the changes you can expect duringa translation.andM;The package shines in the tougher translations--from spreadsheets or text toa database.andP;  Spreadsheet data is displayed in a worksheet format while youdefine fields and highlight ranges to build the database.andP;  For ASCII text,you create a data dictionary onscreen with the text in view.andP;  The utilitythen saves the dictionary so you can use it the next time you make thatconversion.andM;Before you spring for DMBS/Copy, though, take a look at your existingsoftware's import/export capabilities.andP;  Packages such as Borland's QuattroPro spreadsheet read and write several databases and spreadsheets quickly andeasily.andP;  Many packages have dBASE III, Lotus 1-2-3, and comma-delimited ASCIItranslations.andP;  These are often enough.andO;</TEXT></DOC>